```perl
$str =~ /pattern/;         # match
$str =~ s/old/new/g;       # substitute
$str =~ tr/a-z/A-Z/;       # transliterate
if ($str =~ /^(\w+)/) {
    print "$1\n";
}
```
**Regex** is Perl's superpower. `=~` binds, `!~` negates. Captures in `$1`, `$2`, etc.

```perl
open(my $fh, '<', 'file.txt') or die $!;
while (<$fh>) {
    chomp;
    print "$_\n";
}
close($fh);
```
**File I/O** uses three-arg open. `<` read, `>` write, `>>` append. `<$fh>` reads line by line.

```perl
use strict;
use warnings;
```
**strict** and **warnings** should always be enabled. They catch typos and common bugs.

```perl
my $x = 10;
my @list = (1, 2, 3);
my %map = (key => 'val');
```
**my** declares a lexically scoped variable. Always preferred over package globals.

```perl
our $VERSION = '1.0';
our @EXPORT = qw(func1 func2);
```
**our** declares a package global variable. Visible across the package. Use sparingly.

```perl
sub greet {
    my ($name) = @_;
    return "Hello, $name!";
}
my $result = greet('World');
```
**sub** defines a subroutine. Arguments in `@_`. Use `my` to unpack. Returns last expression or explicit `return`.

```perl
chomp(my $line = <STDIN>);
chomp(@lines);
```
**chomp** removes the trailing newline from a string. Safe to call multiple times. Returns number of chars removed.

```perl
my @fields = split(/,/, $line);
my @words = split(' ', $text);
my ($user, $pass) = split(/:/, $entry, 2);
```
**split** divides a string by a pattern. Third arg limits the number of fields.

```perl
my $csv = join(',', @fields);
my $path = join('/', @parts);
```
**join** concatenates list elements with a separator string.

```perl
push @array, $value;
push @array, @more_values;
```
**push** appends elements to the end of an array. Returns the new array length.

```perl
my @doubled = map { $_ * 2 } @numbers;
my @upper = map { uc($_) } @strings;
```
**map** transforms each element of a list. Returns a new list. The block receives `$_`.

```perl
my @evens = grep { $_ % 2 == 0 } @numbers;
my @matches = grep { /pattern/ } @lines;
```
**grep** filters a list. Returns elements where the block evaluates to true.

```perl
my @sorted = sort @array;
my @num = sort { $a <=> $b } @numbers;
my @rev = sort { $b cmp $a } @strings;
```
**sort** orders a list. `<=>` for numeric, `cmp` for string comparison. `$a`/`$b` are special sort variables.

```perl
while (my $line = <$fh>) {
    chomp $line;
    # process
}
```
**Diamond operator** `<>` reads one line at a time. Returns `undef` at EOF. `<STDIN>` reads from standard input.

```perl
open(my $fh, '<', $file) or die "Cannot open $file: $!";
die "Something went wrong" unless $condition;
```
**die** throws an exception. Usually paired with `or` for error handling. `$!` contains the system error.

```perl
eval {
    # risky code
    1;
} or do {
    my $err = $@;
    warn "Caught: $err";
};
```
**eval** block catches exceptions. Check `$@` for error. The block form is preferred over string eval.

```perl
package Dog;
sub new {
    my ($class, %args) = @_;
    return bless \%args, $class;
}
sub bark { print "Woof!\n" }
```
**bless** associates a reference with a class (package). This is Perl's OOP mechanism.

```perl
use strict;
use warnings;
use File::Basename;
use List::Util qw(sum max min);
```
**use** loads a module at compile time. `qw()` imports specific functions. Equivalent to `BEGIN { require Module; Module->import(...) }`.

```perl
require 'config.pl';
require Module::Name;
```
**require** loads a file or module at runtime. Unlike `use`, it doesn't call `import()`.

```perl
package MyApp::Utils;
use Exporter 'import';
our @EXPORT_OK = qw(helper_func);
```
**package** declares a namespace. Use `Exporter` to make functions importable by other code.

```perl
my @list = qw(apple banana cherry);
use POSIX qw(floor ceil);
```
**qw()** creates a list of strings split on whitespace. No commas or quotes needed.

```perl
print "Hello, World!\n";
print $fh "data\n";
print STDERR "error\n";
```
**print** outputs to a filehandle (default STDOUT). No parentheses needed. Does not add newline.

```perl
use feature 'say';
say "Hello, World!";
say $fh "data";
```
**say** is like `print` but automatically adds a newline. Requires `use feature 'say'` or `use v5.10`.

```perl
printf "%-20s %5d %8.2f\n", $name, $age, $score;
sprintf("%.2f", $value);
```
**printf** formatted output. `sprintf` returns the string instead of printing.

```perl
if (exists $hash{key}) { ... }
if (exists $array[5]) { ... }
```
**exists** checks if a hash key or array index has been defined. Doesn't trigger autovivification.

```perl
delete $hash{key};
delete $array[3];
```
**delete** removes a key from a hash or an element from an array.

```perl
if (defined $value) { ... }
my $name = $input // 'default';
```
**defined** checks if a value is not `undef`. `//` (defined-or) provides a default for undefined values.

```perl
foreach my $item (@list) {
    print "$item\n";
}

for my $i (0 .. $#array) {
    print "$i: $array[$i]\n";
}
```
**foreach** iterates over a list. `for` and `foreach` are interchangeable. `$#array` is the last index.

```perl
while (<$fh>) {
    chomp;
    process($_);
}

while (my ($k, $v) = each %hash) {
    print "$k => $v\n";
}
```
**while** loops. Commonly used with filehandle reads and `each` for hash iteration.

```perl
unless ($condition) {
    print "Not true\n";
}
die "Error" unless $ok;
```
**unless** is the opposite of `if`. Executes when the condition is false. Avoid `unless ... else`.
